# Development rules

## Application bundle

- The application bundle that is generated and available at dist/Code.js is a compiled version of the application code.
- Elements written in formHtml at /src/WebFormTemplate.ts must not contain typescript references since the final bundle is pure javascript.

## New features

- Features are generic and reusable across different forms. Do not hardcode specific use cases into the feature logic, always use configuration to define the use case behavior.
- New user-facing strings, form configuration, documentation, and examples must be authored in English only. Do not add or maintain French or Dutch translations for new work unless the human developer explicitly asks for a targeted migration of existing legacy content.
- When creating new features, always add diagnostic logs at the web form level and specific feature logs. This logs need to surface on the top of the web form, to be easily visible in DevTools console.
- Update the SetupInstructions.md file to reflect the new feature (step by step instructions).
- Update the config_schema.yaml file to reflect the new feature (yaml schema for the new feature). This file is used by LLMs to generate form configuration, it need to provide clear and descriptive information.
- Update the README.md file to reflect the new feature (high level overview).
- Create unit tests to cover the new feature.
- Lint is part of the Definition of Done / DLC and must be run for every change before completion.
- Use `npm run lint:changed` as the required lint gate for local feature work. This script compares changed lines against the baseline commit defined in `scripts/lint-changed.js` (`DEFAULT_LINT_BASE_REF`) unless `LINT_BASE_REF` overrides it.
- `npm run lint:changed` is the authoritative guard while the repository still carries an intentional warning baseline. Do not treat the existing warning baseline as permission to introduce new lint findings on changed lines.
- `npm run lint` remains useful for visibility across the full repo, but it is not the main enforcement mechanism while the baseline cleanup is still in progress.
- Run typescript lint verification and fix errors and new warnings introduced by your change.
- Run unit tests to ensure the new feature works as expected. Fix failures and update the tests to cover the new feature.
- Run `npm run build` to ensure the application can be compiled successfully.
- Before starting a new feature, create a solution design and implementation plan. Split the work into logical slices that can be tracked, bring value, can be tested, and make sense to be committed individually.

## Deployment flow (staging only, mandatory)

- Deployments should be primarily done with `npm run deploy:firebase-web-app`.
- `npm run deploy:firebase-web-app` is the normal staging web app deploy path because it deploys Firebase-hosted web assets first and then updates the Apps Script web app shell.
- Use `npm run deploy:apps-script` only when the human developer explicitly asks for an Apps Script-only deploy, or when forcing an embedded rollback with `CK_WEB_ASSET_MODE_OVERRIDE=embedded`.
- Do not deploy by manually copy/pasting `dist/Code.js` in the Apps Script editor.
- Do not run `clasp push` or `clasp deploy` directly.
- Do not create new web app deployments for this project.
- Always deploy to **staging** only.
- Keep `DEPLOY_ENV=staging` in `.env.deploy.staging`.
- The human developer owns `CLASP_DEPLOYMENT_ID` and `CLASP_TARGET_WEB_APP_URL` values in `.env.deploy.staging`.
- Honor `.env.deploy.staging` as the source of truth for deployment id and target web URL.
- Do not override, regenerate, or replace deployment id / web URL values unless the human developer explicitly asks for it.
- Treat lint as part of CI/CD for staging deploys. `npm run deploy:firebase-web-app` and its underlying deploy scripts must run the lint gate before tests/build/deploy.
- The deploy-time lint gate is `npm run lint:changed`, not a raw full-repo eslint run, because the repo currently uses a baseline commit to allow historical warnings while blocking new ones.
- Before deploying, run `npm run build` (or rely on the build steps inside `npm run deploy:firebase-web-app`).
- After deploying, refresh the page before validating behavior.
- After deployment changes, run validation tests using Playwright.

## Architecture, separation of concerns, and scalability

- Separation of concerns is mandatory. Every change must preserve clear boundaries between **UI rendering**, **UI state/orchestration**, **domain/business rules**, **application use cases**, and **infrastructure/API/IO**.
- Do not add new business logic to monolithic or legacy components/services. When a touched area is not following these boundaries, improve the touched slice by extracting or routing the changed behavior through the correct layer instead of contributing more non-compliant code.
- Scope the cleanup to the touched behavior. Do not start a broad rewrite unless the task explicitly asks for it, but never use "legacy file already does this" as a reason to add more rendering, state, domain, and IO logic into the same block.

### Frontend structure

- `src/web/react/App.tsx` is the app shell only. It may compose hooks/components and wire high-level callbacks, but new record lifecycle, dialog, transport, dedup, report, upload, cache, navigation, or status-transition logic must live in focused hooks or helpers.
- App-level hooks and shell helpers belong under `src/web/react/components/app/` or a more specific `src/web/react/features/<feature>/hooks/` folder when the concern is feature-owned.
- `src/web/react/components/FormView.tsx` is the form orchestration shell only. New guided-step, overlay, validation, upload, blur, autosave-hold, or section/group logic must be extracted into feature hooks, components, or domain helpers.
- `src/web/react/components/form/LineItemGroupQuestion.tsx` is the line-item orchestration shell only. New row rendering, row-flow rendering, table rendering, source-first rendering, upload rendering, subgroup rendering, overlay-open rendering, compact-row logic, availability/utilisation derivation, or row mutation rules must live under `src/web/react/features/lineItems/`, `src/web/react/features/uploads/`, `src/web/react/features/utilisations/`, `src/web/react/features/steps/`, or another focused feature folder.
- `src/web/react/components/` is for shared, low-level, feature-neutral UI components. Feature-specific components must not be added there.
- `src/web/react/features/<feature>/components/` contains React rendering components that receive resolved values and callbacks. Components in this folder should not own persistence, transport, or cross-feature business rules.
- `src/web/react/features/<feature>/hooks/` contains React state machines and orchestration for a feature. Hooks may coordinate effects and call injected services, but should delegate pure decisions to domain helpers.
- `src/web/react/features/<feature>/domain/` contains pure TypeScript rules and projections. Domain modules must not import React, DOM APIs, browser globals, Apps Script globals, network clients, or mutable singleton state.
- `src/web/react/features/<feature>/services/` contains feature-specific client-side service adapters only when a shared API layer is not appropriate. Services must be injected into hooks/components rather than imported into pure domain modules.
- `src/web/react/app/` is for app-wide pure helpers and shell policy helpers that are not owned by a specific feature. Prefer a feature folder when the logic has a clear feature owner.
- Shared low-level constants belong in `src/constants/`; configuration normalization/validation belongs in `src/config/`; generic domain rules belong in `src/domain/` only when they are not specific to the React app.

### Backend structure

- `src/services/WebFormService.ts` and `src/services/WebFormTemplate.ts` must remain compatibility/orchestration boundaries. Do not add large new business workflows there when a focused module can own the behavior.
- Apps Script backend logic should be split into focused modules under `src/services/webform/` by concern, such as submissions, follow-up, templates, analytics, lifecycle, data sources, and scheduler behavior.
- Cloud Run API handlers should remain thin request/response adapters. Domain decisions and repository operations must live behind focused services/repositories under `cloud-run/api/`.
- Repository modules own infrastructure details for Sheets, Drive, Firestore, Gmail, and other IO. Domain/use-case modules must receive repositories/adapters through parameters instead of importing platform-specific clients directly.
- Shared backend business rules should be pure TypeScript where possible and reused conceptually across Apps Script and Cloud Run instead of being duplicated in each runtime.

### Import direction and boundaries

- Imports must flow from outer layers to inner layers: UI components -> hooks/orchestration -> domain/use-case helpers -> infrastructure adapters. Inner layers must not import outer layers.
- React components may import hooks, feature components, UI primitives, and domain helpers. They must not call external services, Apps Script APIs, Google APIs, or Cloud Run repositories directly.
- Hooks may import domain helpers and service/API adapters. Hooks should not contain large business-rule branches that can be tested as pure functions.
- Domain helpers may import only types, constants, and other pure helpers.
- Infrastructure adapters may import API clients and platform globals, but they must expose typed functions/results to the rest of the application.
- Avoid circular dependencies. If a circular import appears, split shared types/helpers into a lower-level module.

### Legacy touch rule

- Do not keep unused or legacy code paths after replacing behavior. Remove stale helpers, flags, aliases, comments, tests, docs, and configuration in the same slice when they are no longer needed.
- Compatibility code for existing production data must be explicit: name the compatibility reason, keep it isolated behind a focused helper or adapter, cover it with tests, and remove it once the supported data shape no longer requires it.
- Do not add new fallback branches for superseded terminology or behavior unless they are required to read existing records. If required, keep the external/client-facing language current and confine the older terms to the smallest compatibility boundary.
- When editing a file that mixes rendering, state, business logic, and IO, first identify the smallest coherent part related to the task that can move to the correct layer.
- If adding a new condition, projection, parser, formatter, field mapping, row mutation rule, validation rule, transport decision, or status transition, put it in a domain/helper/use-case module and call it from the legacy file.
- If adding a new visual branch or repeated JSX block, put it in a focused component and inject callbacks/data from the parent.
- If adding stateful UI coordination, put it in a hook unless the state is trivially local to a small component.
- If a fully compliant extraction is too risky for the current slice, do the smallest safe extraction, add or update tests for the extracted behavior, and leave a clear TODO only when further decomposition genuinely requires a separate slice.

### Size, reuse, and tests

- Prefer composition over inheritance. Keep files small; if a module grows beyond ~200–300 lines, consider splitting before adding more code. Large compatibility shells may exceed this temporarily, but new logic must move outward to focused modules.
- Reuse logic through shared utilities, hooks, components, and domain helpers, not by duplicating code. If similar code exists in two places, extract or reuse the shared version as part of the touched slice.
- Prefer explicit typed interfaces at module boundaries, including request/response models and DTO mapping. Validate untrusted inputs at the boundary.
- Keep configuration and constants centralized. No magic strings should be scattered across the codebase when a named constant or config field can express the behavior.
- Keep state local by default. Promote state upward only when multiple siblings need it. Avoid global state for transient UI concerns.
- Unit test domain logic. Add focused tests for new parsers, projections, gates, row mutation rules, and business decisions. Use integration/service tests for adapters and use UI/Playwright tests only for user-visible flows.
- Every new module should have a clear owner and a short doc comment when the responsibility or boundary is not obvious from the module name.

## Miscellaneous

- When the user request that you commit changes to the repository, always use Conventional Commits format.
- Commit messages must include a brief description of the changes in the commit body, not only the subject line.

